 Venezuela is one of the places in the world with cheapest price of gasoline. Fuel so heavily subsidized that a full tank costs close to nothing ― a tiny fraction of the worth of one dollar. The country has been hit with hyperinflation making its currency significantly weakened. Presently, 1 naira = 27 Venezuelan Boliver. Coupled with the heavy subsidised gas price, the motorists in Venezuelan are now paying with bag of rice, cooking oil, cigarette, candy bar and any other thing within reach whenever they do not have cash in their wallet. Continue reading Trade By Barter: Venezuela’s motorists paying for gas with cigarettes, bag of rice at Vanguard News. Source: Vanguard The ban by the Federal Government on imported food items coupled with the closure of surrounding borders to avoid their smuggling into the Nigerian market, has not only continued to affect their prices adversely, especially that of imported rice, a major staple food in Nigeria, but has made the commodity… August 11, 2019 In "News" A major challenge confronting today’s tobacco market is illicit trade.  The Financial Action Task Force (FATF), a global inter-governmental body, defines illicit trade in tobacco as “the production, import, export, purchase, sale or possession of tobacco goods, which fail to comply with legislation.” In Nigeria, there are aspects of the… July 12, 2017 In "News" Items                      Prices Basket of Tomatoes                        N15,500 – N25,000 A bag of Pepper  (Rodo)                               N 10,000 – N18,000 A bag of Long pepper                     N6, 500 – N7000 A bag of Onions (white)  … December 6, 2017 In "News"